  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Solvi Landfill Gas-to-Energy and Solar Cap Feasibility Study. Solvi Landfill Gas-to-Energy and Solar Cap</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support the creation, improvement and sustainability of physical infrastructure, and related services, in both urban and rural areas, to enhance the economic environment and improve economic productivity, including for women. The main infrastructures include energy, including electric power transmission lines and distribution networks, oil/gas terminals, refineries, storage facilities and pipelines; telecom and ICT; and transport, including roads, airports, railways, and ports.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This award supports the creation, improvement and sustainability of physical infrastructure, and related services, in both urban and rural areas, to enhance the economic environment and improve economic productivity, including for women,. More specifically, this award includes a Solvi Landfill Gas-to-Energy and Solar Cap Feasibility Study. This grant funds the Solvi Landfill Gas-to-Energy and Solar Cap Feasibility Study for Solvi Valorizacao Energetica in Brazil. This study will evaluate the technical, economic, and financial feasibility of implementing a suite of landfill energy projects at five sites managed by Solvi Valorizacao Energetica, a Brazilian private waste management company.. This grant funds the Solvi Landfill Gas-to-Energy and Solar Cap Feasibility Study for Solvi Valorizacao Energetica in Brazil. This study will evaluate the technical, economic, and financial feasibility of implementing a suite of landfill energy projects at five sites managed by Solvi Valorizacao Energetica, a Brazilian private waste management company. Specifically, the study will assess the feasibility of landfill gas-to-energy production with gas engine-generator sets at four designated landfill sites, the development of anaerobic bioreactors at these sites to enhance the methane yield, the development of state-of-the art gas conditioning systems for the landfills, and finally, the feasibility and conceptual design for a solar cap system at a fifth site that would generate renewable solar energy..</narrative>
  </description>
